level_description_from_recommendations_v: Add one daily serving of fiber-rich food (e.g., oats or beans)
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: Fiber supports metabolic health, digestive function, and cardiovascular resilience. It helps the body eliminate excess cholesterol, regulates blood sugar, and promotes a healthier gut microbiome. Found in foods like oats, beans, flaxseed, and psyllium, soluble fiber is a foundational component of a longevity-supportive diet.

level_description_from_recommendations_v: Limit saturated fat sources to ≤2 per day
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: Swapping saturated fats for healthier fats like olive oil, avocados, nuts, and fatty fish supports heart and brain health, lowers systemic inflammation, and promotes metabolic balance. These fats are core components of dietary patterns linked to increased longevity and reduced chronic disease risk.
title_from_recommendations_v2: Prioritize Healthy Fats Over Saturated Fats

level_description_from_recommendations_v: Maintain a 2:1 ratio of healthy to unhealthy fat sources daily

level_description_from_recommendations_v: Limit alcohol consumption to no more than 1 drink per day
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: Alcohol affects liver health, metabolic function, sleep quality, inflammation, and hormonal balance. For users with elevated GGT, ALT, hsCRP, or disrupted sleep, moderating or removing alcohol intake can lead to significant improvements in biomarker trends and subjective well-being over a 3–4 month protocol.

level_description_from_recommendations_v: Limit alcohol consumption to no more than 2 drinks per day
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: Alcohol affects liver health, metabolic function, sleep quality, inflammation, and hormonal balance. For users with elevated GGT, ALT, hsCRP, or disrupted sleep, moderating or removing alcohol intake can lead to significant improvements in biomarker trends and subjective well-being over a 3–4 month protocol.

level_description_from_recommendations_v: Limit added sugar to one serving - any food or drink with about 8–12g of added sugar (e.g., 1 cookie, sweetened yogurt, granola bar, or can of soda). If the item is over 15g, count as 2 servings.) of food or drink with added sugar per day
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: Added sugar contributes to metabolic dysfunction, inflammation, and increased chronic disease risk. Reducing daily added sugar improves energy, supports healthy weight, and protects long-term cardiometabolic health. For this recommendation, a serving is any food or drink with about 8–12g of added sugar (e.g., 1 cookie, sweetened yogurt, granola bar, or can of soda). If the item is over 15g, count as 2 servings.

level_description_from_recommendations_v: Limit added sugar to no more than two servings - any food or drink with about 8–12g of added sugar (e.g., 1 cookie, sweetened yogurt, granola bar, or can of soda) per week
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: Added sugar contributes to metabolic dysfunction, inflammation, and increased chronic disease risk. Reducing daily added sugar improves energy, supports healthy weight, and protects long-term cardiometabolic health. For this recommendation, a serving is any food or drink with about 8–12g of added sugar (e.g., 1 cookie, sweetened yogurt, granola bar, or can of soda). If the item is over 15g, count as 2 servings.

level_description_from_recommendations_v: Limit processed meat to no more than 3 servings per week
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: High intake of processed meats is linked to increased cancer, cardiovascular, and metabolic disease risk. Reducing processed meat supports longevity and promotes healthier eating.

level_description_from_recommendations_v: Limit processed meat to no more than one serving per week and aim for a diversity of unprocessed protein sources
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: High intake of processed meats is linked to increased cancer, cardiovascular, and metabolic disease risk. Reducing processed meat supports longevity and promotes healthier eating.

level_description_from_recommendations_v: Wake up by a set time (e.g., 8:00am) on weekends and weekdays
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: Consistent wake times anchor the circadian clock, support better sleep quality, and improve daily energy patterns.

level_description_from_recommendations_v: Limit non-work screen time to less than 4 hours daily
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: Reducing non-work screen time supports better focus, healthier sleep patterns, and improved mental well-being. Non-work screen time refers to recreational or passive use of digital devices outside of job-related responsibilities—such as watching videos, scrolling social media, playing games, or browsing aimlessly.

level_description_from_recommendations_v: Limit non-work screen time to less than 3 hours daily
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: Reducing non-work screen time supports better focus, healthier sleep patterns, and improved mental well-being. level_description_from_recommendations_v: Limit non-work screen time to less than 2 hours daily
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: Reducing non-work screen time supports better focus, healthier sleep patterns, and improved mental well-being. level_description_from_recommendations_v: Limit to 5 or fewer cigarettes daily
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: Reducing smoking immediately improves cardiovascular and lung health.

level_description_from_recommendations_v: Reduce caffeine intake to ≤400mg per day on all 7 days of the week
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: High caffeine intake (over 400mg/day) can disrupt sleep, increase anxiety, and impact blood pressure. Reducing intake supports better sleep, energy, and cardiometabolic health. 1 regular cup of coffee ≈ 100mg, 1 espresso ≈ 60–80mg, 1 energy drink ≈ 80–120mg, 1 cup of tea ≈ 40mg.

level_description_from_recommendations_v: Finish all caffeinated beverages by 2pm every day of the week
overviewn_from_recommendations_v2: Consuming caffeine late in the day can disrupt sleep, delay circadian rhythms, and reduce sleep quality. To support optimal sleep and energy, finish all coffee, tea, energy drinks, and other sources of caffeine by 2pm.
